attn_out stage 1: structural change needed; wide-tile dead-end

Status: tsk-58 (wide-tile follow-ups) closed negative; option 3 tried
and regressed.

Results of wide-token-tile (64-tok) experiment:
  wide32 baseline:   stage 1 10.25 ms/call,  attn_out_q8_batch 18.1 ms/call
  wide64 candidate:  stage 1 ~17.6 ms/call,  attn_out_q8_batch 25.5 ms/call (-7% prefill)

Root-cause analysis:
* Stage 1 wide32 achieves only ~65 GB/s effective DRAM (666 MB weight /
  10.25 ms) -- 35% of the 188 GB/s ceiling.  So stage 1 is NOT
  memory-bound; the bottleneck is compute/latency/occupancy.
* Wide-token doubles live VGPR pressure (4 accumulators + 4 B operands
  vs 2+2 in wide32).  Likely halves wave occupancy on gfx1151, which
  is the dominant cost given we are already latency-bound.
* Wide-rank (option 2) has the SAME VGPR pressure as wide64 and saves
  zero DRAM (block count halves but per-block weight reads double),
  so it would not differ.

Remaining options on this kernel:
* Option 1 (LDS staging) requires multi-wave block restructure (sharing
  activation slab in LDS across rank tiles within a block).
  Substantial rewrite; uncertain payoff given we are not memory-bound.
* Option 4 (FA prefill layout [group, token, group_dim]) addresses the
  root strided access pattern.  Touches prefill + decode + batch FA
  variants.  Invasive but theoretically the cleanest win.

Deferred for now: stage 1 at 10.25 ms/call x 43 layers = 440 ms per
prefill (~9% of wall).  Top bucket is routed_moe_batch at ~62 ms/call.
Next leverage is MoE, not attn_out stage 1.

